<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="UTF-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>Geotechnical Engineering in Juneau Alaska</title><meta name="description" content="Soil mechanics study for Juneau construction. We run lab and field programs under ASTM and IBC standards, tailored to"><link rel="canonical" href="https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/"><meta property="og:type" content="website"><meta property="og:title" content="Geotechnical Engineering in Juneau Alaska"><meta property="og:description" content="Soil mechanics study for Juneau construction. We run lab and field programs under ASTM and IBC standards, tailored to"><meta property="og:url" content="https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/"><meta property="og:site_name" content="Geotechnicalengineering"><meta property="og:locale" content="en_US"><meta property="og:image" content="https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/img/estudio-mecanica-suelos-1.webp"><meta property="og:image:width" content="1200"><meta property="og:image:height" content="630"><meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image"><meta name="twitter:title" content="Geotechnical Engineering in Juneau Alaska"><meta name="twitter:description" content="Soil mechanics study for Juneau construction. We run lab and field programs under ASTM and IBC standards, tailored to glacial and marine soils in Southeast Alaska."><meta name="twitter:image" content="https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/img/estudio-mecanica-suelos-1.webp">
<script type="application/ld+json">{"@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [{"@type": "LocalBusiness", "@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#org-e422", "name": "Juneau Alaska", "url": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/", "email": "info@geotechnicalengineering.sbs", "address": {"@type": "PostalAddress", "addressLocality": "Juneau Alaska", "addressCountry": "USA"}, "geo": {"@type": "GeoCoordinates", "latitude": 58.302, "longitude": -134.4197}, "areaServed": {"@type": "City", "name": "Juneau Alaska"}}, {"@type": "Service", "@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#service-e422", "serviceType": "Soil mechanics study", "name": "Geotechnical Engineering in Juneau Alaska", "description": "Soil mechanics study for Juneau construction. We run lab and field programs under ASTM and IBC standards, tailored to glacial and marine soils in Southeast Alaska.", "provider": {"@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#org-e422"}, "areaServed": {"@type": "City", "name": "Juneau Alaska"}, "url": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/"}, {"@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/", "url": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/", "name": "Geotechnical Engineering in Juneau Alaska", "inLanguage": "en", "isPartOf": {"@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#website-e422"}}, {"@type": "WebSite", "@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#website-e422", "url": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/", "name": "Juneau Alaska", "inLanguage": "en"}, {"@type": "FAQPage", "@id": "https://juneau-alaska.geotechnicalengineering.sbs/#faq-e422", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "What does a soil mechanics study cost for a residential lot in Juneau?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "For a single-family lot on a typical hillside or valley site in Juneau, a soil mechanics study with index tests, classification, and a factual report ranges between US$2,810 and US$5,700. The final figure depends on the number of borings, depth to refusal, and whether consolidation or triaxial testing is required. Sites with thick organic silt or fill near the Mendenhall wetlands tend to need more lab hours."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How long does lab testing take after samples arrive from the field?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Standard index tests (moisture content, Atterberg limits, sieve and hydrometer) are completed within five to seven working days. Consolidation and triaxial tests add eight to fourteen days because of the staged loading and saturation requirements under ASTM D2435 and D4767. We schedule the program so preliminary classification data reaches the design team while strength tests are still running."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can you test frozen or disturbed samples from a winter drilling program?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "We can test partially frozen samples for moisture content and gradation once they thaw under controlled lab conditions, but strength and consolidation tests require undisturbed specimens. If the sample shows ice lensing, cracks, or swelling from freeze-thaw, we flag it in the report and recommend resampling during the May-to-October window when ground temperatures in Juneau are above freezing at the sampling depth."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Which ASTM standards do you follow for a soil mechanics study on a commercial foundation?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Classification follows ASTM D2487. Moisture content uses ASTM D2216. Atterberg limits follow ASTM D4318 multi-point method. Particle-size analysis uses ASTM D6913 for the coarse fraction and D7928 for the hydrometer. Consolidation runs under ASTM D2435, and triaxial compression under ASTM D4767. All reporting references IBC Chapter 18 for foundation design applicability."}}]}]}</script>
